    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-10-19T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-10-19T16:00:00-05:00" n="830"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d830">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 652.119/1916</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul at Curaçao</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Messersmith</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-10-19T17:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 19, 1918, 5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your October 8, 11 a.m. We have transmitted the following cable to the American
                    Consul at Puerto Cabello: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>War Trade Board requires Spanish steamer <hi rend="italic"
                                >Villamanrique</hi> to call at Porto Rico after leaving Venezuela
                                <hi rend="italic">en route</hi> to Canaries and Spain.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>[The War Trade Board, in considering the plan proposed on October 16 for
                        examining neutral vessels proceeding across the Atlantic to or from northern
                        neutral countries, considered also a plan for examining in a port of Porto
                        Rico or of the United States, Spanish vessels proceeding to or from Spain.
                        These plans, however, were not approved by the Department of State. See <hi
                            rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_1003">pages 1003</ref>, <ref
                            target="#pg_1010">1010</ref>, and <ref target="#pg_1012"
                        >1012</ref>.]</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
        </body>
